Claims CLAIMS The invention claimed may be: 1 . A metal oxide nanostructure formed on the surface of a substrate, comprising: a first layer comprising a plurality of tubular structures; and a second layer comprising a lattice structure; wherein the first layer is situated between the substrate and the second layer. 2. The metal oxide nanostructure of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the substrate comprises an alloy of nickel and titanium. 3. The metal oxide nanostructure of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the tubular structures comprise titanium oxide and nickel oxide in a ratio greater than or equal to 1 :1 . 4. The metal oxide nanostructure of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the plurality of tubular structures are aligned generally perpendicular to the substrate and generally parallel to one another. 5. The metal oxide nanostructure of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the plurality of tubular structures each have an outer surface, and wherein the outer surface of each of the plurality of tubular structures are in contact with the outer surfaces of each of the adjacent tubular structures. 6. The metal oxide nanostructure of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the lattice comprises titanium oxide and nickel oxide. 7. The metal oxide nanostructure of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the ratio of titanium oxide to nickel oxide on the distal surface of the lattice is greater than or equal to 10:1 . 8. The metal oxide nanostructure of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the substrate is an implantable medical device. 9. The metal oxide nanostructure of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the substrate is a stent. 10. The metal oxide nanostructure of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein first and second layers are formed on a surface of the substrate using electrochemical anodization. 1 1 . A biocompatible surface formed on a surface of a stent, comprising: a first layer comprising a plurality of tubular structures aligned generally perpendicular to the surface of the stent; and a second layer comprising a metal oxide lattice defining openings therein; wherein the first layer is situated between the surface of the implantable medical device and the second layer; wherein the plurality of tubular structures each have an outer surface, and wherein the outer surface of each of the plurality of tubular structures are in contact with the outer surfaces of each of the adjacent tubular structures; and wherein a distal surface of the metal oxide lattice comprises titanium oxide and nickel oxide, with the ratio of titanium oxide to nickel oxide being greater than or equal to 10:1 . 12. The biocompatible surface of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the surface promotes the growth of human aortic endothelial cells at an interface between the stent and an artery. 13. The biocompatible surface of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the surface inhibits the growth of smooth muscle cells at an interface between the stent and an artery. 14. A method of modifying the surface of an article, comprising: anodizing at least a portion of a surface of an article in a first electrolyte solution, wherein the first electrolyte solution does not contain an acid; and 

 anodizing the portion of the surface of the stent in a second electrolyte solution, wherein the second electrolyte solution contains an acid. 15. The method of modifying the surface of an article of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the article is anodized in the first electrolyte solution for about 5 minutes at about 25 V. 16. The method of modifying the surface of an article of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the article is anodized in the second electrolyte solution for about 5 minutes at 25 V. 17. The method of modifying the surface of an article of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the article comprises nickel and titanium. 18. The method of modifying the surface of an article of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the article is an implantable medical device. 19. The method of modifying the surface of an article of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the article is a stent. 20. The method of modifying the surface of an article of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the acid in the second electrolyte is hydroiodic acid. 21 . The method of modifying the surface of an article of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the acid in the second electrolyte is sulfuric acid. 22. The method of modifying the surface of an article of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the acid in the second electrolyte is lactic acid. 23. The method of modifying the surface of an article of any one or more of the preceding claims, wherein the acid in the second electrolyte is citric acid. 24. A method of forming a metal oxide nanostructure comprising the steps of: placing an anode and at least one cathode in electrical contact through a first electrolyte solution comprising an organic solvent, a fluoride-bearing species, and water; 

 applying a first voltage across the anode and cathode through the first electrolyte solution for a first time period; modifying or replacing the first electrolyte solution resulting in a second electrolyte solution comprising an organic solvent, a fluoride-bearing species, water, and an acid; and applying a second voltage across the anode and cathode through the second electrolyte solution for a second time period. 25. The method of forming a metal oxide nanostructure of any one or more of the preceding claims, further comprising providing an anode comprising nickel and titanium and alloys thereof and a cathode. 26. A method of preparing a biocompatible surface comprising the steps of: placing an anode and at least one cathode in electrical contact through a first electrolyte solution comprising an organic solvent, a fluoride-bearing species, and water; applying a first voltage across the anode and cathode through the first electrolyte solution for a first time period; removing a portion of the anode surface; applying a second voltage across the anode and cathode through an electrolyte solution for a second time period. 27. The method of preparing a biocompatible surface of any one or more of the preceding claims, further comprising providing an anode comprising nickel and titanium and alloys thereof and a cathode. 28. Any combination of above features is within the scope of the present disclosure.
